{"cursor":"15350","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox settlement |name = Ratnapuara |native_name =  |nick_names =\nRuwanpura, Minipura |image_skyline = |image_caption = |image_flag = |image_seal\n= |image_map = |map_caption = |pushpin_map = Sri Lanka |pushpin_label_position =\nLocation of Ratnapura within Sri Lanka |pushpin_mapsize = |coordinates_region =\nLK |coordinates_type = |settlement_type = City |subdivision_type = Country\n|subdivision_name = |subdivision_type1 = Province |subdivision_name1 =\nSabaragamuwa Province |subdivision_type2 = District |subdivision_name2 =\nRatnapura District |government_type = Municipal Council |leader_title = Mayor\n|leader_name = |area_magnitude = |area_total_km2 = 20 |population_as_of = 2011\n|population_footnotes = |population_total = 52,170 |population_demonym = Demonym\n|population_demonym = Ratnians |population_density_km2 = 2474 |timezone = SLT\n|utc_offset = +05:30 |latd=6 | latm=40 | lat NS=N |longd=80 | longm=24 | long\nEW=E |elevation_m = 130 |website = |footnotes = }} 'Ratnapura' (; ) (\"City of\nGems\" in Sinhala and Tamil) is a major city in Sri Lanka. It is the capital city\nof Sabaragamuwa Province, Sri Lanka and the Ratnapura District. Some say the\nmodern name is derived from the Portuguese name Rapadura for jaggery, the palm\ncandy produced traditionally in this region, but the more common explanation in\nSri Lanka is that it comes from the Sinhala \"ratna\" meaning gems and \"pura\"\nmeaning city. Ariyaratna, D. H., President of the Sri Lanka Gem Association\nof the UK, Gems of Sri Lanka, 6th revised edition, 2006, self-published, p.\n31. Ratnapura is also spelled as Rathnapura. Located some 101Â km\nsouth east of capital Colombo.\n\nIt is the centre of a long-established industry of precious stone mining\nincluding rubies, sapphires, and other gems. Apart from gem mining, the city is\nknown for rice and fruit cultivations. Large plantations of tea and rubber\nsurround the city. Tea grown in this region is called low-country tea. There is\na well-established tourism industry in Ratnapura. Sinharaja Forest Reserve,\nUdawalawe National Park, Kitulgala, and Adam's Peak are especially popular\namong tourists.\n\nIn 1901, the town of Ratnapura had a population of 4,084, and in 2011, it\nhad increased to 52,170 and this consisted of Buddhist, Hindus, Christians\nand Muslims.\n","linknr":332,"url":"Ratnapura","recorded":1375054515,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Ratnapura&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Ratnapura&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/City","/wiki/File:Sri_Lanka_location_map.svg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6e/Sri_Lanka_location_map.svg/250px-Sri_Lanka_location_map.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/0/0c/Red_pog.svg/6px-Red_pog.svg.png","//tools.wmflabs.org/geohack/geohack.php?pagename=Ratnapura&params=6_40_N_80_24_E_type:city(52170)_region:LK","/wiki/List_of_countries","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/11/Flag_of_Sri_Lanka.svg/23px-Flag_of_Sri_Lanka.svg.png","/wiki/Sri_Lanka","/wiki/Province","/wiki/Sabaragamuwa_Province","/wiki/Districts_of_Sri_Lanka","/wiki/Ratnapura_District","/wiki/Municipal_Council","/wiki/D